What Scala is.

Scala is a statically typed, hybrid functional and object-oriented language that targets the java virtual machine. Martin Odersky designed it at the swiss federal institute of technology in 2004, with one goal — keep the engineering pragmatism of java, the libraries, the java virtual machine, the tooling, and fuse it with the expressive power of the m-l family of functional languages. The name is a contraction of scalable language. The same syntax should feel right for a five-line script and for a million-line distributed system.

Four traits define Scala in one breath. The key insight is that each one shapes how the code you write later will read.

First, it is statically typed but inference-heavy. The compiler catches type errors at build time, but you rarely write the types yourself, because the compiler infers most of them for you.

Second, functions are values. You pass them as arguments, return them from other functions, and store them in collections, exactly like integers or strings.

Third, it is immutable by default. A val, which is a single-assignment binding, is preferred over a var, which is a mutable variable. Standard-library collections are immutable unless you explicitly import the mutable ones.

Fourth, it runs on the java virtual machine. Every java library on the central maven artifact repository is reachable from Scala with no ceremony — same classpath, same dot-class files, same bytecode.
